Mango: Quick Start

Jennifer Chang
10 February 2015

Open Mango

  1. Open Mango and you should be presented with the following screen.
  1. The Log Console (bottom right) is where you can type and execute Gel commands. All Gel commands end with a semicolon symbol. Type the following into the Log Console and press Enter/Return:
setwd();

Log Console

  1. setwd pops a window to allow you to select the current working directory. This directory may contain your graph or Gel script files. Navigate and Select the DemoFiles folder that came with Mango installation.

Loading Graph Data

  1. Now we are going to load 4 graph files. To save typing, we will be using the run command to execute Gel scripts saved in a plain text file. Type the following Gel command into the Log Console:
run "loadnet.txt";
  1. In the DataView Control (left), expand Graphs and Values. Four graphs are listed inside of Graph. Click on their names and visualizations of the selected graph will appear in the GraphCanvas (right center) on separate tabs. Tabs are labeled with the graph names. you can drag and rearrange the tabs or show multiple graphs at once.

Navigating the Graph Canvas

  1. The GraphCanvas (right center) area responds to mouse and keyboard events. Left click and drag across a graph. This will rotate the graph visualization.

  2. Use the Roller Ball on your mouse (or two finger swipe on the trackpad) to zoom in and out of a graph.

  3. Making sure one of the graphs is selected (the tab label will be bolded) use the arrow keys on your keyboard to move the graph left, right, up, and down.

  4. Next, Right click on one of the displayed graphs. The graph should start to move with connected nodes moving closer together and disconnected nodes moving farther apart. This is the force-directed layout algorithm porposed by Eades. Right click again to stop animating the layout.

Graph Layouts

  1. To explore some other default graph layouts, select one fo the graphs and type the following Gel commands into the Log Console. Try rotating, zooming, and running the force-directed algorithm after each command.
layout("circle");
layout("cube");
layout("random");

A closer look at one graph

  1. Close all tabs except graph cpn. Run the following command:
layout("cube");
  1. Right click to start the force directed layout. To turn on and off node labels type the following GEL Command:
text("node");
  1. With the cursor after the prompt “>>>” in the Log Console, use the up arrow keys to recall previous commands and execute the text command again to turn labels off.

Graph Addition

  1. To combine multiple Graphs, GEL has a set of graph mathematics. Enter the following GEL commands into the Log Console, ignoring the comments after the “//” symbols:
run "loadnet.txt";        // resets original layouts
graph(nt,lt) sum = aldo;  // creates new graph called sum
  1. Click on sum in DataViewControl to display hte graph. Then run the following GEL commands to add in the remaining three graphs and notice how the visualization of sum changes.
sum .+= cpn;
sum .+= frh;
sum .+= hif;

Graph Subtraction

  1. Notice how aldo, frh, and hif graphs are connected to one another while cpn is not. Remove cpn with the following command:
sum .-=cpn;
  1. Right-click sum to start the force-directed layout algorithm. Let run for a while and then stop.

Graph Export

  1. Change your working directory to the place you want your graph file saved.
setwd();      /* Pops a window, select Desktop or elsewhere */
  1. Export the new graph file of sum with the following command:
export("sum.csv","csv",sum);

* You can also type the full pathname to a location instead of changing the current directory.

  1. The graph file sum.csv, located in your selected folder, contains the combined graph, listing nodes and links with attributes.
